dump: Dendritic cells derived from mouse bone marrow hematopoietic stem cells in vitro

Dendritic cells (DCs), first described by Steinman &Cohn in 19731, are the uniquely professional antigen-presenting cells that play crucial roles in the initiation and regulation of immune responses2. They are located at surveillance sites where they capture and process antigens. Recent evidence points to DCs as pivotal cells that are necessary for initiation and maintenance of the alloantigen-specific immune response. Dendritic cells not only activate lymphocytes to induce the immune response, but they also minimize autoimmune reactions by tolerizing T cells to self-antigens3. Immature dendritic cells (DCs) have the tolerogenic potential to induce alloantigen-specific immune tolerance2. It has been shown that infusions of DC lacking cell surface costimulatory molecules will prolong survival of allograft, whereas in vitro manipulation of DC by exposure to a variety of factors (e.g. IL-10 and transforming g
re dendritic cells pulsed with peptides into healthy patients results in inhibition of specific T-cell responses to the injected peptides.

Whereas, now we have to face another problem: the DCs are some cells without the capacity of proliferation as well as their tiny quantity in the peripheral blood or tissue, while to induce immunotolerance may need a large number of immature DCs. How can we get these cells? Hematopoietic stem cells(HSC), are cells with capacity of selfrenewal and self duplication, can differentiate into all kinds of hemocytes. A part of HSC may be stored, while other part of then may be used o differentiate DCs. After the former part be exhausted, the part that be stored can be expanded and proliferated and repeat above schedule. Thus these characteristics of HSC can be used to get permanent source of DCs.

The differentiation pathway of DCs from HSC has not been fully clarified. Nevertheless, it is clear now that there are three main ways to get HSC: from bone marrow, from cord blood and from peripheral blood. The
